V. Phase IV: Foundational Dispute Architecture (The FCRA
Mandate)
The successful application of the CFTCAP depends entirely on translating the identified technical and structural
flaws into legally compliant dispute requests that compel the furnisher to initiate an investigation. The "shortcut"
requires strict adherence to the language and requirements established under FCRA Section 611(a) and
Regulation V, Â§ 1022.43.
Defining a Valid Direct Dispute (Â§ 1022.43)
Regulation V establishes three mandatory categories of consumer disputes that a furnisher must investigate:
liability, account terms, and consumer performance/conduct. Every dispute generated in the preceding phases
must be precisely mapped to one of these categories to prevent the furnisher from dismissing the claim as
frivolous or irrelevant.
1. Consumer's Liability: This covers disputes related to identity theft, fraud, joint/individual liability, or
authorized user status. PII fragmentation (Phase I) falls under this category, forcing the DF to verify the
identity linked to the account.
2. Account Terms: This category includes disputes concerning the type of account, principal balance,
scheduled payment amount, or the credit limit on an open-end account. Disputes regarding inconsistent High
Credit/Credit Limit fields (Phase III) are categorized here.
3. Consumer Performance or Conduct: This encompasses current payment status, date of payment, amount
paid, or high balance. Disputes regarding contradictory 30-day late marks (Phase III) are categorized here.
Dispute Categorization and Prioritization
By grouping the audit findings into priority tiers, resources can be allocated for maximum impact and velocity:
Tier 1 (High Priority/Quick Wins): These are easily verifiable, fundamental data mapping failures. PII
errors (e.g., incomplete DOB on Experian) and inquiry duplicates (e.g., Nissan hard pulls) are primary targets.
These issues demand minimal external documentation but highlight clear, demonstrable failures in the Metro
2 formatting or system synchronization.
Tier 2 (Medium Priority/Technical Audits): These disputes require presenting comparative bureau data
(e.g., TU report vs. EXP report) to illustrate the contradiction in fields like High Credit or Date Last Active.
Examples include the inconsistent dates for the MACYS/CBNA account or the contradictory late payment
marks on the AM HONDA FIN accounts.
Tier 3 (Strategic/Long-Term): These are disputes designed to manage the overall risk profile without
seeking deletion. The primary focus here is mitigating the high CUR by disputing the accuracy of reported
balances or limits on actively used cards, providing a slow-burn strategy for utilization management.
